        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="evo-bench-terminal">
        <div class="evo-bench-terminal-header">
          <div class="evo-bench-terminal-dot"></div>
          EvORanker — Ranked Output
        </div>
        <div class="evo-bench-terminal-body">
          <div class="evo-bench-case">PATIENT: Family 1 — psychomotor delay, dysphasia, hyperactivity</div>
          <div class="evo-bench-label-line">CANDIDATES: 47 rare homozygous variants</div>
          <div class="evo-bench-row evo-bench-row-header">
            <span>RANK</span><span>GENE</span><span>FISHER p-VALUE</span><span>SIGNAL</span>
          </div>
          <div class="evo-bench-row evo-bench-rank-1">
            <span>1</span><span>DLGAP2</span><span>1.65 &times; 10&#8315;&#8310;</span><span>NPP + STRING</span>
          </div>
          <div class="evo-bench-row">
            <span>2</span><span>SYNGAP1</span><span>3.12 &times; 10&#8315;&#8308;</span><span>NPP (Mammalia)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="evo-bench-row">
            <span>3</span><span>CNTNAP2</span><span>4.87 &times; 10&#8315;&#8308;</span><span>NPP (Chordata)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="evo-bench-row">
            <span>4</span><span>…</span><span></span><span></span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="evo-bench-terminal-footer">Reconstructed from case data reported in Canavati et al., <em>Genome Medicine</em>, January 2024. Gene names and top candidate p-value are from the paper; secondary ranks are illustrative of the output format.</div>
      </div>

      <p>On 91 solved patient exomes with autosomal or X-linked recessive inheritance (from a total cohort of 109 exomes), EvORanker identified the correct disease gene as the top-ranked candidate in 69% of cases and within the top five in 95%. On the dominant subset, performance was slightly different: 67% top-ranked, 95% within the top 10 — note the shift from top-5 to top-10. On a simulated benchmark of 900 artificial patients with 300 unique diseases, recessive accuracy reached 75% top-ranked and 96% within the top five; dominant accuracy was 55% top-ranked and 85% within the top ten.</p>
      <p>Compared to existing tools, EvORanker outperformed both ExomeWalker and PHIVE in 30% of 108 exome cases. It outperformed at least one of the two in 74%. The comparison that matters most has not been done: EvORanker was not benchmarked against Exomiser, the most widely used gene-prioritization tool in clinical genomics. The 69%/95% figures cannot be directly compared to Exomiser's reported performance without a controlled head-to-head study. The story of EvORanker's advantage is specific: it is strongest where annotation-dependent tools are weakest — on poorly characterized genes. Phylogenetic profiling alone yielded significant p-values for 45% of newly annotated genes (those added to disease databases between 2020 and 2022), compared to 38% for STRING alone.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="phantom-wrap">
      <canvas class="evoranker-rare-disease-canvas" aria-hidden="true"></canvas>
    </div>
    <p class="canvas-note"><strong>The Convergence Point</strong> — A field of dim gene-dots sits in stillness. Faint wave-fronts ripple inward from different directions, each too weak to illuminate anything alone. Where multiple waves intersect, one dot slowly brightens to emerald as the evolutionary signal accumulates. The glow holds. The waves dissipate and the dot dims back to anonymity. New waves arrive from different angles and converge on a different point.</p>

    <section class="section" id="cases">
      <h2><span class="num">03 — The Cases</span>Three Families, Three Genes</h2>
      <p>The benchmarks show what EvORanker can do on cases that have already been solved. The unsolved cases show why it was built.</p>
      <p><strong>Family 1: DLGAP2.</strong> The patient was a child with psychomotor delay, dysphasia, hyperactivity, and poor attention span. Whole-exome sequencing produced 47 rare homozygous variants. EvORanker ranked DLGAP2 first, with a combined Fisher p-value of 1.65 × 10<sup>−6</sup>. The co-evolving genes that drove the signal — GRIN2A, NLGN1, CNTNAP2, SYNGAP1, GABRA5 — are established players in synaptic function and neurodevelopmental disorders. The variant (NM_001346810:c.A2702T, p.Glu901Val) was validated by a minigene splicing assay, which showed it activated a cryptic splice site causing a four-base-pair deletion, frameshift, and premature termination. Homozygous DLGAP2 knockout mice recapitulate the clinical picture: novelty-induced hyperactivity, increased aggression, impaired reverse learning.</p>
      <p><strong>Family 2: LPCAT3.</strong> The patient was a child with failure to thrive, chronic diarrhea, muscle atrophy, elevated liver enzymes, and high creatine kinase. EvORanker ranked LPCAT3 first. The variant (NM_005768:c.G939A, p.W313X) was homozygous and truncating. This case is the clearest demonstration of the annotation-bottleneck argument. STRING — the protein-interaction database that most existing tools rely on — could not detect LPCAT3's association. Only the clade-based phylogenetic profiling found it, with a p-value of 7.93 × 10<sup>−15</sup>. LPCAT3 was too poorly characterized in human disease literature for annotation-dependent methods to recognize it. The mouse model concordance was precise: LPCAT3 knockouts show intestinal impairment with abnormal enterocyte morphology and lipid accumulation; liver-specific knockouts display hepatosteatosis and reduced triglycerides. The patient's duodenal biopsies showed severe enteropathy with partial villous blunting. Plasma triglycerides were 34 mg/dL. HDL was 27.1 mg/dL.</p>
      <p><strong>SUPT4H1: Three Families Across Three Countries.</strong> In a 2026 paper published in <em>Genetics in Medicine</em> (Volume 28, Issue 5, May 2026), Canavati, Tabach, and 24 collaborators across institutions in Israel, Norway, and Spain reported that biallelic variants in SUPT4H1 cause a multisystem neurodevelopmental disorder — intellectual disability, dystonia, speech impairment, craniofacial dysmorphism, skeletal anomalies, and enamel hypoplasia — in three unrelated families. EvORanker is listed in the paper's keywords and contributed to the identification. The full text is behind a paywall, and the precise extent of EvORanker's role — whether it was the primary discovery tool or a supplementary analysis — cannot be confirmed from the accessible abstract. What can be confirmed: dopamine treatment improved motor symptoms in the affected individuals.</p>
      <p>Before this work, SUPT4H1 was known only as a transcription elongation factor studied in basic research. It had no human disease association. It was a variant of uncertain significance. It is now linked to a defined disorder with a treatment response documented across families on three continents.</p>

